[Project] Hoiktronics: Reset Mechanisms

  1. DicemanX Brain of Cthulhu

    Start a Conversation
    ZeroGravitas released a video today showcasing the first ever Terraria computer:



    The compactness due to hoiks being very efficiently used is amazing! As we utilize hoiktronics to build bigger contraptions, I wanted to take a quick opportunity to explore reset mechanisms because some of the more elaborate contraptions will need them to avoid having to pull a myriad of levers or switches. ZeroGravitas showcased a vertical reset in his video (which I'm hoping he'll elaborate on, since it's not so easy to follow the hoiking in such a compact structure), and in the meantime I present my two attempts at horizontal reset mechanisms. Here they are:



    Wiring:



    The idea is to send a skeleton pulse using the bottom hoik. In the bottom reset mechanism , any time the ground below one of the teeth is actuated, the skeleton takes the alternate path down, across, then up, passing over a pressure plate and re-setting whatever is attached via wire back to it's original state. The mechanism essentially checks every state (binary ON or OFF states) and reverts every state back to its original setting.

    The top reset mechanism is completely analogous, and the alternate paths are top, right, then down relative to the horizontal hoik.

    There are two issues with both mechanisms:

    1) They only work for skeletons, not for player NPCs or player characters
    2) They only work underground, or at night (daytime above 0 altitude = skeleton gets stuck)

    Now the good news is that they work perfectly underground so they apply to underground contraptions at all times, but I still want to see if reset mechanisms can be built that have no restrictions at all and remain fairly compact.

    Can anyone propose better horizontal reset mechanisms?

    Here's another approach:





    Works with skeletons underground - still need to test above ground. There is sometimes a slight pause at one of the teeth, but the skeleton always goes through. Doesn't work well with NPCs because they can get stuck if they try to move to the left while in the hoik. The player character works though.


    EDIT: Success!



    I removed the in-between teeth in the upper hoik and now it works perfectly with skeletons and player NPCs day or night overground or underground. Very compact too.

    So there we have it - a very efficient restart mechanism!

  5. ZeroGravitas The Destroyer

    Start a Conversation
    DicemanX said: ↑
    I removed the in-between teeth
    Click to expand...
    Yup, that's what I was going to say. This is just like my reset design I've tried to explain before, I think. For those who don't understand, it works by tweaking the NPC/player's precise vertical position in the following step: bottom hoiks put you against the floor on the next step (hitting a floor plate, if there is one), while top hoiks leave you on the ceiling, skipping over the pressure plate without activating it!

    DicemanX said: ↑
    Very compact too.
    Click to expand...
    Not enough for my liking, tbh. The problem is that the plate has to be linked with the actuated teeth in the step behind it. This means that you need 2 steps per plate/wire to keep the wiring separate. You *can* get them adjacent, with interwoven wiring, but it requires alternating all 3 wire colours, which leaves no provision for overlapping wires for other mechanisms (that will inevitably be needed for more complex machines).

  10. ZeroGravitas The Destroyer

    Start a Conversation
    Got it! Took my brain-mush long enough, but finally iterated my way there. I don't think you'll be able to beat this for compactness:

    8 bit reset line. Varies between 8 ticks and 16 ticks to run the length of the switches, depending on how many are in the 'on' state; it toggles between top hoik (2 tile step left) and wiast high bottom hoik (1 tile step left, twice). After thinking up the mis-matched hoik types, the key was figuring out that I didn't have to actuate the second bottom hoik tooth in each pair.

    I incorporated this into my newest version of the digi-comp which I will post later, and I found out that this set-up only works if the skeleton runs from right to left - the mirror image set-up doesn't work because the skeleton gets stuck on the first up deactuated hoik (skeleton is stuck on the left in the pic):



    Of course there's no problem when the mirror image of the reset mechanism is used, so this post is just a word of caution to those wanting to use this mechanism - make sure you build it running from right to left. Otherwise, it works perfectly . Good thing too because my newest version of the digicomp can use the more compact set-up!
